If its period of oscillation is \(\text{T'}\), then the ratio \(\text{T'}\)/\(\text{T}\) is
explanation_txt:
Moment of inertia of original magnet

\(I = \cfrac{ml^2}{12} \)

When magnet is broken in two parts, then

\(I' = \cfrac{(m/2)\times (l/2)^2}{12} = \cfrac{1}{8} I \)

\(\therefore \) Time period \(T = 2 \pi \sqrt{ \cfrac{I}{MB} } \)

\( \cfrac{T'}{T} = \sqrt{ \cfrac{I'}{I} \times \cfrac{M}{M'}} = \sqrt{ \cfrac{I}{8I} \times \cfrac{M}{(M/2)}} = \cfrac{1}{2} \\ \therefore \cfrac{T'}{T} = \cfrac{1}{2} \)
